1. Definitions

"Covered Software" means TrustLink Kernel and any source, object, build,
documentation, interface, protocol, or derivative work distributed with this
repository.

"Licensor" means Alik "Lord" Gaynetdinov and any legal entity or successor
authorized by him to license the Covered Software.

"Licensee" means any person or entity exercising rights under this license,
including its affiliates, subsidiaries, contractors, and controlled entities.

"Use" means to copy, run, modify, compile, publish, distribute, host, embed,
provide over a network, or otherwise exploit the Covered Software.

"Commercial Use" means Use that directly or indirectly supports revenue,
funding, paid products, paid services, internal business operations, hosted
services, resale, consulting delivery, advertising, marketplace activity, or
any other business advantage.

"Gross Revenue" means all revenue, receipts, service fees, subscription fees,
license fees, advertising revenue, marketplace fees, transaction fees, grants,
and other consideration received by Licensee and its affiliates before costs,
taxes, refunds, chargebacks, or expenses are deducted.

"Covered Offering" means any product, service, platform, company, application,
device, network, hosted system, or internal system that uses, embeds, depends
on, or is materially enabled by the Covered Software.

"Revenue Threshold" means 10,000,000 Russian rubles in Gross Revenue during
any trailing twelve-month period, or the equivalent in another currency using
the official exchange rate published by the Central Bank of the Russian
Federation on the last day of that period.

2. Public Grant Below The Threshold

Subject to this license, Licensor grants Licensee a non-exclusive, worldwide,
royalty-free right to Use the Covered Software for evaluation, research,
education, non-commercial projects, internal development, and Commercial Use
while Licensee and its affiliates remain below the Revenue Threshold.

This grant does not transfer ownership. Licensor keeps all copyright, patent,
trade secret, trademark, and other rights not expressly granted here.

3. Commercial Royalty Trigger

If Licensee or any Covered Offering reaches or exceeds the Revenue Threshold,
Licensee must obtain a signed commercial license from Licensor before continued
production Commercial Use. If the threshold is crossed after lawful use began,
Licensee has thirty calendar days to contact Licensor and execute the required
commercial license.

After that thirty-day period, any production Commercial Use is unlicensed until
a commercial license is signed and all overdue amounts are paid.

4. Default Commercial Terms

Unless Licensor signs different written terms, the required commercial license
must include all of the following economics:

a. Royalty. Licensee must pay Licensor seven percent (7%) of Gross Revenue
attributable to each Covered Offering. If Licensee does not separately track
attributable revenue in reliable accounting records, Licensee must pay two
percent (2%) of Licensee's total Gross Revenue instead.

b. Equity. If the Covered Offering is owned or operated by a private company,
Licensee must cause that company to issue Licensor five percent (5%) of the
company's fully diluted equity, economically equivalent to founder common
equity and protected from dilution on terms no worse than the best founder or
early employee class then outstanding. If equity issuance is legally impossible
or the company is publicly listed, Licensee must sign an economically
equivalent cash, token, warrant, synthetic equity, or revenue-share arrangement
acceptable to Licensor before continued production Commercial Use.

c. Reporting. Royalties are calculated quarterly and paid within thirty days
after each calendar quarter. Licensee must provide a good-faith revenue report
showing Covered Offerings, calculation method, currency conversion, and payment
amount.

d. Records and audit. Licensee must keep accurate records for at least three
years. No more than once per year, Licensor may audit records relevant to this
license through an independent professional under confidentiality obligations.
If an audit finds an underpayment above five percent (5%), Licensee must pay
the audit cost in addition to the underpaid amount.

